  <section>
    <h2>Context: why Australia's share is so high</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Points-based migration system:</strong> Australia has used a skills-based selection system since 1973, systematically prioritising labour market needs. This produces a large and economically active immigrant cohort.</li>
      <li><strong>Geographic isolation:</strong> Unlike European countries, Australia receives very little spontaneous unauthorised migration. The overwhelming majority of immigrants are selected through formal channels.</li>
      <li><strong>Historical settlement patterns:</strong> Post-WWII immigration programs from Europe, followed by the removal of the White Australia Policy in 1973, created successive waves of permanent settlement.</li>
      <li><strong>Definition used:</strong> ABS uses "overseas-born" (place of birth), which includes naturalised citizens. This is comparable to the "foreign-born" measure used in Nordic and other European country pages on this site.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Comparison with other Western countries</h2>
    <p>Among the 20 Western countries tracked by Immigration Factbook, Australia's 32% foreign-born share is the highest, followed by New Zealand (~28.8%), Switzerland (~27.7%), and Canada (~23%). By comparison, France stands at ~11.3% foreign nationals and Germany at ~25.6% including migration background (a broader definition).</p>
    <p>Direct comparison requires caution: countries use different definitions (foreign-born vs. foreign nationals vs. migration background). See the <a href="/en/themes/comparison-matrix/">20-country comparison matrix</a> for definitions used per country.</p>
  </section>

